						<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://www.pawm.ca/2012/01/energy-and-capital-newsletter-circa-june-2008/" rel="bookmark">Energy and Capital newsletter circa June 2008</a></h1>
			
						<div class="entry-meta">
				<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="http://www.pawm.ca/2012/01/energy-and-capital-newsletter-circa-june-2008/" title="6:21 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2012-01-04T18:21:58+00:00">January 4, 2012</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://www.pawm.ca/author/sean/" title="View all posts by Sean" rel="author">Sean</a></span></span>			</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			
						<div class="comments-link">
				<a href="http://www.pawm.ca/2012/01/energy-and-capital-newsletter-circa-june-2008/#respond"><span class="leave-reply">Reply</span></a>			</div>
					</header><!-- .entry-header -->

				<div class="entry-content">
			<p>Here&#8217;s a blast from the past from the PAWM archives: Energy and Capital&#8217;s newsletter extolls the virtues of investing in water wealth. While you may not be thinking of having a water meter hanging on your well in the future, the prospect is attractive to investors looking to find new ways to monetize existing resources.</p>
<p><a title="eandcnewsletter.pdf" href="http://www.pawm.ca/docs/eandcnewsletter.pdf" target="_blank">Click on the link</a> to view the PDF file.</p>
